Interactively review and add submissions

Summary:
This changes the old script that just displays user submissions that can be
added, and displays a prompt asking whether a submission should be added. If
yes, will insert, else, will record it was rejected (and skip it in future
runs).

This just inserts a row into our table of known plugin github repos, which will
be used when we run the github scraper. A future revision will use the saved
`from_submission` field to auto-populate category and tags.

Test Plan:
- ran `make review_submissions` locally
- responded "y" a bunch of times
- ctrl-c'ed the script
- re-ran. saw that the "yes" submissions were not displayed again and added to
  the count of "known github plugins" and reduced the count of "new plugins".
  Also ran some DB queries to see that new rows were inserted into
  the `plugin_github_repos` table.
- responded "n" a bunch of times
- saw the rejected plugins count go up, new plugins count go down accordingly
- also ran a DB query filering on `rejected: true` to verify

Add and use vim.org submission data

Summary:
We used to just ignore vim.org submissions because we'd scrape them anyway.
However, user submissions include category and tags data that we can update
plugin rows with, which is what this revision does.

Test Plan:
- ran `make review_plugins`
- reviewed two vim.org plugins and accepted them
- ran `PYTHONPATH=. python tools/scrape/scrape.py -s vim.org`
- checked that the accepted submitted plugins have their category and tags correctly set

Upgrade rethinkdb to 1.16.1

I was sort of forced to do this after having accidentally upgraded the server's
rethinkdb to 1.14 in September when trying to patch that bash vulnerability.
This caused the data format on the server to not work with 1.13. This came up
as a problem when trying to deploy -- `make init_db` failed because rethinkdb
>= 1.14 removed the `upsert=True` parameter. So I upgraded both the server and
my local rethinkdb version to the latest, 1.16.1, and then fixed all usages of
`upsert=True` to the new `conflict="replace"` argument.

Test Plan:
- ran `make`
- ran `make init_db`
- hit `localhost:5001/`
- ensured things work!
